---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { SITE } from '../lib/site';
---

<Layout
  title="How We Research Trends & Write Worth-It Buying Briefs"
  description="How HotPick Lab researches trending products — signal selection, brief structure, verdicts, updates, and editorial independence."
  keywords={['editorial methodology', 'product research process', 'worth it reviews', 'buying briefs']}
>
  <article class="prose methodology-page">
    <h1>How we research</h1>
    <p class="method-lead">
      HotPick Lab exists for one job: help you decide <strong>buy, skip, or wait</strong> on a
      trending product before you spend money or start a subscription.
    </p>

    <h2 id="signals">1. What we cover</h2>
    <p>We focus on US-market products with a spike in search or social attention and real purchase intent:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Amazon trending</strong> — viral physical products (home, fitness, seasonal gear)</li>
      <li><strong>AI tools</strong> — video, photo, and creator SaaS with subscription decisions</li>
      <li><strong>Gaming & hobby</strong> — first-buy accessories and beginner gear</li>
      <li><strong>Seasonal commerce</strong> — Prime Day and holiday deal windows</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>2. How we select a topic</h2>
    <p>A topic becomes a brief only if all three pass:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><strong>Signal</strong> — search interest, seasonal demand, or a launch cycle is active</li>
      <li><strong>Decision clarity</strong> — we can give a useful verdict for a defined audience</li>
      <li><strong>Honest skip</strong> — we can name who should not buy, not just who should</li>
    </ol>
    <p>If we cannot add a structured decision, we wait.</p>

    <h2>3. How each brief is built</h2>
    <p>Every buying brief follows the same frame so you know what to expect:</p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Why it is trending</strong> — context, not hype</li>
      <li><strong>Who it is for / who should skip</strong> — fit before features</li>
      <li><strong>Before you buy</strong> — pitfalls buyers miss in reviews</li>
      <li><strong>Compared picks</strong> — usually 2–4 options, with pros and cons</li>
      <li><strong>Verdict</strong> — buy, skip, or wait (for a sale or better alternative)</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>4. What we do — and do not — claim</h2>
    <p>
      We synthesize specs, pricing, buyer feedback patterns, and category knowledge. We do
      <strong>not</strong> run a Wirecutter-scale testing lab. When a brief is research-based rather
      than hands-on tested, we say so and focus on decision fit — not fake bench scores.
    </p>

    <h2>5. How we stay independent</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Retailers and brands do not pay for placement in our briefs</li>
      <li>Skip recommendations are part of the product — we earn nothing when you skip</li>
      <li>Affiliate links are disclosed on every monetized page</li>
      <li>Editorial picks are made before commission rates are considered</li>
    </ul>
    <p><a href="/disclosure">Full affiliate disclosure →</a></p>

    <h2>6. Updates</h2>
    <p>
      Trending products change fast. Each brief shows a <strong>last researched</strong> date. We
      revise picks when prices, product lines, or hype materially shift — especially before major
      retail events.
    </p>

    <h2>7. Free research tools</h2>
    <p>
      Tools like our deal calculator and aspect-ratio helper support the same decision moment as
      our briefs. They work standalone — bookmark them even if you never read a full guide.
    </p>
    <p><a href="/tools">Browse research tools →</a></p>
  </article>
</Layout>

<style>
  .method-lead {
    font-size: 1.1rem;
    color: #d9e2ff;
    max-width: 42rem;
  }

  .methodology-page ol {
    padding-left: 1.2rem;
  }
</style>
